*Exercise 1.1:* Build your own whole Human Gene Annotation file using
Biomart ENSEMBL. Once you have built your gene annotation file load the
gencode file GRCh37 of gene annotations at the dropbox link below, you
should chose a few random genes that are at different genome locations
and compare their positions at the genome in both Gene Annotations
(e.g.Â ENSEMBL-Biomart and Gencode version). Are the genomic coordinates
of genes the same as those that has been used in the previous sessions?.
Hint: to build a data.frame with information similar to the Gencode
Annotation File you must select in biomart those attributes to build you
own an annotation file for all genes within human genome.

``` r
# Dado un archivo de anotacion
gencode <- read.table("https://www.dropbox.com/s/jpn22hwswgk69wr/gencode_GRCh37.txt?dl=1",
                      header=TRUE,
                      stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
# Observar el contenido
head(gencode)
```

``` r
# Observar las columnas que tiene para hacer un archivo similar
colnames(gencode)
```

    ## [1] "gene_id"    "gene_name"  "chromosome" "start"      "end"       
    ## [6] "strand"     "type"

``` r
# Seleccionar los datos que vamos a tener nuestro propia anotacion
ensembl_genes <- useEnsembl(biomart = "genes", dataset = "hsapiens_gene_ensembl")

# Ver que columnas hay
available.Attributes = listAttributes(ensembl_genes)
head(available.Attributes)
```

    ##                            name                  description         page
    ## 1               ensembl_gene_id               Gene stable ID feature_page
    ## 2       ensembl_gene_id_version       Gene stable ID version feature_page
    ## 3         ensembl_transcript_id         Transcript stable ID feature_page
    ## 4 ensembl_transcript_id_version Transcript stable ID version feature_page
    ## 5            ensembl_peptide_id            Protein stable ID feature_page
    ## 6    ensembl_peptide_id_version    Protein stable ID version feature_page

``` r
# Buscar cual es el nombre de las columnas parecidas a las de gencode:
#"gene_id"    "gene_name"  "chromosome" "start"  "end"        "strand"     "type" 
searchAttributes(mart = ensembl_genes, pattern = "gene_id")
```

*Exercise 2.1:* Using the BioMart-Gencode version of the previous
exercise, try to generate an annotation data frame adding information
about the location of the exons within the two longer genes in the
chromosome that has been assigned to you. Include for each exon their
corresponding ENSEMBL IDs, start and end positions as well as the
transcript ID that the exon belong. Provide the total number of exons,
take care of not counting more than once each value.

``` r
# Definir my chromosoma
mychr <- 21
# Hacer una tabla de mis datos
df <- getBM(attributes = mycols,
      filters = "chromosome_name",
      values = mychr,
      mart = ensembl_genes)

# Crear una columna en mis datos llamada lenght
df$lenght <- df$end_position - df$start_position
# Ordenar la columna con los tamanos orden descendente + a -
df <- df[order(-df$lenght),]
# Obtener los ids de los genes mas largos
head(df,2)
```

``` r
# Hacer una lista de las columnas que necesito
mycols = c("ensembl_gene_id", "external_gene_name", "chromosome_name", "start_position", "end_position", "gene_biotype","transcription_start_site")

# Hacer una table con mis datos de genes
df <- getBM(attributes = mycols,
      filters="chromosome_name",
      values=mychr,
      mart=ensembl_genes)

# Obtener los tamanos de los genes
df$lenght <- df$end_position - df$start_position

# Ordenar en orden descendente + a -
df <- df[order(-df$lenght),]

# Obtener los ids de los genes mas largos
longest_gene = head(df,1)
longest_gene
```
